### Typography Scale

Use a modular scale. Choose a ratio based on content type:

| Ratio | Name | Best for |
|-------|------|----------|
| 1.125 | Major second | Dense UI, dashboards, admin |
| 1.200 | Minor third | General-purpose, SaaS |
| 1.250 | Major third | Marketing, editorial |
| 1.333 | Perfect fourth | Landing pages, storytelling |
| 1.500 | Perfect fifth | Hero-driven, dramatic |

```css
--text-xs:   clamp(0.70rem, 0.65rem + 0.25vw, 0.80rem);
--text-sm:   clamp(0.80rem, 0.75rem + 0.25vw, 0.90rem);
--text-base: clamp(0.95rem, 0.90rem + 0.25vw, 1.05rem);
--text-lg:   clamp(1.15rem, 1.05rem + 0.50vw, 1.30rem);
--text-xl:   clamp(1.40rem, 1.20rem + 1.00vw, 1.80rem);
--text-2xl:  clamp(1.75rem, 1.40rem + 1.75vw, 2.50rem);
--text-3xl:  clamp(2.20rem, 1.60rem + 3.00vw, 3.75rem);
--text-4xl:  clamp(2.80rem, 1.80rem + 5.00vw, 5.50rem);
```

### Typography Rules

- **Never use just one weight.** A single weight makes hierarchy invisible. Use at least three: regular (400), medium (500), bold (700).
- **Line height decreases as size increases.** Body: 1.5-1.7. Headings: 1.1-1.3. Display: 1.0-1.1.
- **Letter-spacing tightens for large text.** Display: -0.02em to -0.04em. Body: 0. Small caps/labels: +0.05em.
- **Limit line length.** 60-75 characters for body. Use `max-width: 65ch`.
- **Use font-feature-settings.** Enable ligatures, old-style numerals, tabular figures where appropriate.


## 5. Spacing & Rhythm

### Spacing as Design Language

Whitespace is not empty — it's structural. It communicates hierarchy, groups related elements, and creates breathing room.

### The 8pt Grid

Base all spacing on multiples of 8px. For tighter UI, use a 4px sub-grid.

```css
--space-1:  0.25rem;  /* 4px  — hairline gaps, icon-to-label */
--space-2:  0.50rem;  /* 8px  — tight padding, inline spacing */
--space-3:  0.75rem;  /* 12px — compact components */
--space-4:  1.00rem;  /* 16px — default padding, form gaps */
--space-6:  1.50rem;  /* 24px — card padding, section inner */
--space-8:  2.00rem;  /* 32px — section gaps */
--space-12: 3.00rem;  /* 48px — major section breaks */
--space-16: 4.00rem;  /* 64px — page section spacing */
--space-24: 6.00rem;  /* 96px — hero padding, dramatic space */
--space-32: 8.00rem;  /* 128px — full section breathing room */
```

### Vertical Rhythm

- **Sections should breathe unevenly.** Not every section needs the same top/bottom padding. Hero sections get more space. Dense content gets less.
- **Group by proximity.** Elements that belong together should be closer together than elements that don't. This is Gestalt's Law of Proximity — the most important layout principle.
- **Progressive spacing.** Within a section, increase spacing as you move down: heading → body (tight) → CTA (more space). This creates a natural reading cadence.

### Section Pacing

Alternate between dense and spacious sections to create rhythm:

```
[Hero — spacious, dramatic]
[Features — medium density, grid]
[Testimonial — spacious, single quote, full-width]
[Pricing — dense, comparison table]
[CTA — spacious, centered, minimal]
[Footer — dense, utilitarian]
```

This alternation prevents monotony and guides the user through content with natural breathing points.


## 6. Visual Hierarchy

### The Hierarchy Toolkit

Control where the eye goes using these tools, in order of strength:

1. **Size** — Largest element wins. A 72px headline dominates everything.
2. **Color contrast** — High contrast against background draws attention. Your accent color should only appear on what matters most.
3. **Weight** — Bold text in a field of regular text is a magnet.
4. **Position** — Top-left (LTR) gets seen first. Center gets attention. Bottom-right is where the eye exits.
5. **Whitespace** — Isolation draws attention. An element surrounded by space feels important.
6. **Motion** — Anything that moves gets attention. Use sparingly — animation is a loaded gun.

### Hierarchy Patterns

**The Squint Test:** Squint at your screen. If you can still tell what's most important, your hierarchy works. If everything blurs into sameness, you need more contrast between levels.

**Three levels maximum per view:**
- **Level 1** — One thing. The headline, the primary CTA, the key number. Largest, boldest, most colorful.
- **Level 2** — Supporting content. Subheadings, secondary info, navigation. Medium size, medium weight, muted color.
- **Level 3** — Everything else. Body text, labels, metadata. Smallest, lightest, most neutral.

**Common mistakes:**
- Making everything Level 1 (nothing stands out)
- Using color for Level 3 items (labels, metadata) instead of reserving it for Level 1
- Headings that are only slightly larger than body text


## 7. Micro-interactions Catalog

### Hover States

```css
/* Subtle lift — cards, clickable surfaces */
.card:hover {
  transform: translateY(-2px);
  box-shadow: 0 8px 24px oklch(0 0 0 / 0.08);
  transition: all 200ms cubic-bezier(0.33, 1, 0.68, 1);
}

/* Color shift — links, text buttons */
.link:hover {
  color: var(--primary);
  text-decoration-color: var(--primary);
  transition: color 150ms ease;
}

/* Background fill — nav items, list items */
.nav-item:hover {
  background: var(--surface-alt);
  transition: background 150ms ease;
}

/* Scale — icon buttons, small interactive elements */
.icon-btn:hover {
  transform: scale(1.08);
  transition: transform 200ms cubic-bezier(0.34, 1.56, 0.64, 1);
}
```

### Button Feedback

```css
/* Press down effect */
.button:active {
  transform: scale(0.97);
  transition: transform 100ms ease;
}

/* Loading state — swap content, add spinner */
.button[data-loading] {
  pointer-events: none;
  opacity: 0.7;
}
.button[data-loading] .label { opacity: 0; }
.button[data-loading] .spinner { opacity: 1; }
```

### Page Transitions

```css
/* Staggered entrance — the single most impactful animation */
.stagger-item {
  opacity: 0;
  transform: translateY(12px);
  animation: fadeUp 500ms cubic-bezier(0.33, 1, 0.68, 1) forwards;
}
.stagger-item:nth-child(1) { animation-delay: 0ms; }
.stagger-item:nth-child(2) { animation-delay: 80ms; }
.stagger-item:nth-child(3) { animation-delay: 160ms; }
.stagger-item:nth-child(4) { animation-delay: 240ms; }

@keyframes fadeUp {
  to { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); }
}
```

### Scroll Reveals

```css
/* Modern scroll-driven animation (CSS only, no JS) */
@supports (animation-timeline: view()) {
  .reveal {
    opacity: 0;
    transform: translateY(20px);
    animation: scrollReveal linear both;
    animation-timeline: view();
    animation-range: entry 0% entry 30%;
  }
  @keyframes scrollReveal {
    to { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); }
  }
}
```

### Loading States

- **Skeleton screens** over spinners — always. They reduce perceived wait time.
- **Pulse animation** for skeletons: subtle `oklch(0.92 0.005 0)` ↔ `oklch(0.96 0.005 0)` oscillation.
- **Progressive loading** — show content as it arrives, don't wait for everything.
- **Optimistic updates** — reflect the action immediately, reconcile with server after.

### Motion Rules

- **150-200ms** for hover, focus, toggle states
- **250-400ms** for entrances, route transitions, expanding panels
- **400-600ms** for complex orchestrated sequences
- **Use `cubic-bezier(0.33, 1, 0.68, 1)`** (ease-out-quint) as default easing — it feels natural
- **Always respect `prefers-reduced-motion`** — provide `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)` overrides


## 8. Dark Mode Design

Dark mode is not "invert the colors." It's a separate design language with its own rules.

### Core Principles

1. **Reduce chroma by 10-20%.** Colors that look great on white look garish on dark. Desaturate.
2. **Surfaces use elevation, not borders.** Lighter surface = higher elevation. Build depth with layered grays.
3. **Never use pure black (`#000`).** Use `oklch(0.13 0.01 <hue>)` — a very dark, slightly tinted surface.
4. **Text is not pure white.** Use `oklch(0.93 0.005 <hue>)` for primary text. Slightly off-white reduces eye strain.
5. **Shadows are nearly invisible.** In dark mode, shadows don't work. Use subtle borders or surface color differences instead.

### Surface Elevation Scale

```css
/* Dark mode surfaces — lighter = higher */
--surface-base:    oklch(0.13 0.01 250);  /* deepest background */
--surface-raised:  oklch(0.17 0.01 250);  /* cards, panels */
--surface-overlay: oklch(0.21 0.01 250);  /* modals, dropdowns */
--surface-top:     oklch(0.25 0.01 250);  /* tooltips, popovers */
```

### Dark Mode Color Adjustments

```css
/* Light mode accent */
--primary-light: oklch(0.55 0.20 250);

/* Dark mode — reduce chroma, increase lightness */
--primary-dark:  oklch(0.68 0.15 250);
```

### Glow Effects (Dark Mode Only)

In dark mode, glows replace shadows as the primary depth cue:

```css
.dark .glow-element {
  box-shadow:
    0 0 20px oklch(0.55 0.15 250 / 0.15),
    0 0 60px oklch(0.55 0.15 250 / 0.05);
}

/* Glow text for emphasis */
.dark .glow-text {
  text-shadow: 0 0 30px oklch(0.60 0.15 250 / 0.3);
}
```

### Dark Mode Checklist

- [ ] Background is not pure black
- [ ] Text is not pure white
- [ ] Primary accent chroma reduced from light mode
- [ ] Surfaces create depth through lightness, not shadows
- [ ] Borders are subtle (`oklch(1 0 0 / 0.08)`) not harsh
- [ ] Images/illustrations have reduced brightness or a subtle overlay
- [ ] Status colors still meet contrast requirements
- [ ] Focus rings are visible against dark surfaces


## 9. Anti-Patterns: The "AI Slop" Catalog

These patterns scream "generated by AI" and must be avoided. Each has a specific alternative.

### Typography Slop

| Anti-Pattern | Why It's Bad | Do This Instead |
|-------------|-------------|-----------------|
| Inter everywhere | It's the new Arial — invisible, generic | Use Satoshi, DM Sans, Plus Jakarta Sans, or better yet a distinctive display font |
| Roboto, Open Sans, Lato | Overexposed, no character | See font recommendations above |
| System font stack for display text | Signals "I didn't bother choosing" | System fonts are fine for body; use a real font for headings |
| One font weight | Flat hierarchy, no visual interest | Use 3+ weights: 400, 500, 700 minimum |
| Default letter-spacing on large text | Looks loose and unrefined | Tighten to -0.02em or -0.03em for display sizes |

### Color Slop

| Anti-Pattern | Why It's Bad | Do This Instead |
|-------------|-------------|-----------------|
| Purple-to-blue gradient on white | The #1 AI cliche | Any other palette. Earth tones. Monochrome. Warm accents. |
| Evenly distributed rainbow palette | No hierarchy, carnival vibes | 60/30/10 rule with a single dominant hue |
| Pure gray neutrals | Cold, disconnected from brand | Tint neutrals with your primary hue |
| Oversaturated everything | Overwhelming, amateur | High chroma only for accents; muted for surfaces |
| `#000` text on `#fff` background | Harsh, eye-straining | Dark neutral on off-white: `oklch(0.15 0.02 hue)` on `oklch(0.98 0.005 hue)` |

### Layout Slop

| Anti-Pattern | Why It's Bad | Do This Instead |
|-------------|-------------|-----------------|
| Three equal cards in a row | Every AI landing page ever | Vary card sizes, use asymmetric grids, feature one card prominently |
| Centered everything | Monotonous, no visual flow | Mix alignment. Left-align body text. Use asymmetric compositions. |
| Icon + heading + paragraph x 6 in a grid | Template-grade layout | Vary the rhythm. Use different component patterns per section. |
| Fixed 1200px container everything | Desktop tunnel vision | Let some elements break the container. Use full-bleed sections. |
| Uniform section padding | Metronomic, boring | Vary padding based on content density and importance |

### Motion Slop

| Anti-Pattern | Why It's Bad | Do This Instead |
|-------------|-------------|-----------------|
| Everything fades in from bottom | Predictable, monotonous | Vary direction. Some from left, some scale, some just fade. |
| 3D card tilt on hover | Overused since 2020 | Subtle lift, color shift, or border highlight |
| Parallax on every section | Distracting, motion-sickness risk | One parallax moment per page, if any |
| Typewriter effect on every heading | Slow, blocks reading | Use it once for a hero, never elsewhere |
| Bounce/elastic easing everywhere | Juvenile, cartoon-like | `cubic-bezier(0.33, 1, 0.68, 1)` — smooth ease-out |

### Content Slop

| Anti-Pattern | Why It's Bad | Do This Instead |
|-------------|-------------|-----------------|
| "Welcome to [Product]" hero | Says nothing, wastes prime real estate | Lead with the value proposition or a provocative statement |
| Gradient blob/mesh background with no purpose | Pure decoration, no information | If using blobs, make them subtle and contextual |
| Stock-photo-style hero images | Generic, trust-eroding | Use real product screenshots, illustrations, or abstract art |
| "Get Started" as the only CTA text | Vague, low-commitment language | Be specific: "Start building", "See pricing", "Try for free" |
| Fake testimonials with AI headshots | Instantly recognizable, destroys trust | Use real quotes or skip testimonials entirely |


